'''''Half-Earth: Our Planet's Fight for Life''''' is a 2016 book by [[E. O. Wilson]], in which the author proposes that half of the [[Earth]]'s land should be designated a human-free [[natural reserve]] to preserve [[biodiversity]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dreifus |first=Claudia |authorlink=Claudia Dreifus |date=1 March 2016 |title=A plea, while there's still time |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |page=D5 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/01/science/e-o-wilson-half-earth-biodiversity.html}}</ref> Wilson noted that the term "Half-Earth" was coined for this concept by Tony Hiss in his ''[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]]'' article "Can the World Really Set Aside Half the Planet for Wildlife?"<ref>{{cite book |last=Wilson |first=Edward O. |authorlink=E. O. Wilson |date=2016 |title=Half-Earth: our planet's fight for life |location=New York |publisher=[[Liveright Publishing Corporation]], a division of [[W. W. Norton & Company]] |isbn=9781631490828 |oclc=933727398 |pages=3, 213}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Hiss |first=Tony |date=September 2014 |title=Can the world really set aside half of the planet for wildlife? |journal=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]] |volume=45 |issue=5 |pages=1 |url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/can-world-really-set-aside-half-planet-wildlife-180952379/?no-ist}}</ref>

