'''Huey Johnson''' (born 1933) is a self-described environmentalist and the founder of Resource Renewal Institute (RRI), a non-profit organization that deals with environmental sustainability.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meet Huey Johnson|url=http://www.rri.org/about_huey.php|work=Resource Renewal Institute|publisher=Resource Renewal Institute|accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Huey D. Johnson|url=http://hdj.rri.org/|work=Resource Renewal Institute|publisher=Resource Renewal Institute|accessdate=7 July 2012|date=4 February 2008}}</ref> He is also the founder of [[The Trust for Public Land]], the Grand Canyon Trust and the Environmental Liaison Center.<ref>{{cite web|title=Profile: Huey Johnson|url=http://www.ecospeakers.com/speakers/johnsonh.html|work=EcoSpeakers.com|publisher=EcoIQ|accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref> In 2001, Johnson was awarded by the [[United Nations Environmental Programme]] the $200,000 Saskawa Prize, considered one of the world’s most important environmental awards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Huey D. Johnson : Winner 2001|url=http://www.unep.org/sasakawa/winners/huey.asp|work=UNEP Sasakawa Prize|publisher=United Nations Environment Programme|accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref> Huey Johnson’s work in resource management has been praised by [[United Nations]] officials for having a global perspective. The United Nations has also called Johnson "a catalyst and champion for environmental protection”.<ref>{{cite web|title=American environmentalist, Huey Johnson, wins UNITED NATIONS premier environment prize|url=http://www.unep.org/Documents.Multilingual/Default.asp?DocumentID=225&ArticleID=2954|work=UNEP News release 2001|publisher=United Nations Environment Programme|accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref>

From 1978 to 1982, Johnson was [[California]]'s secretary for resources during the [[Jerry Brown]] administration.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=bxgzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sTIHAAAAIBAJ&pg=6803,3374261 | title=New Melones backers demand Johnson ouster | work=[[Lodi-News Sentinel]] | date=3 October 1979 | agency=UPI | accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref> Johnson is known for introducing [[Green Plan]]s, an integrated approach to protecting and managing natural resources, to the [[United States]]. Mr. Johnson believes that these plans are capable of managing [[Climate Change]]. Green Plans, which have been implemented in the [[Netherlands]], [[New Zealand]], Sweden, and [[Mexico City]], provide useful working models to help countries plan for a more sustainable future.<ref>{{cite web|title=Will Americans stand up for parks and open space?|url=http://www.lahopenspace.com/Hjohnson.html|work=Los Altos Hills Open Space|publisher=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=7 July 2012|author=Huey D. Johnson|format=Op Ed.|date=19 June 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Interview: Huey Johnson|url=http://wmsu.org/program.php?id=214|work=New Path Distinguished Speaker Series, MSU Land Policy Institut|publisher=Michigan State University|accessdate=7 July 2012|date=19 March 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219091538/http://wmsu.org/program.php?id=214|archivedate=19 February 2012|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Strategy For A Green Century|url=http://www.context.org/iclib/ic22/johnson/|work=Context Institute|publisher=Global Climate Change|accessdate=7 July 2012|author=W. R. Prescott|page= 35}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Huey Johnson "Green Planning at Nation Scale"|url=http://blog.longnow.org/02008/10/06/huey-johnson-green-planning-at-nation-scale/|work=The Long Now Foundation|publisher=The Long Now Foundation|accessdate=7 July 2012|author=Stewart Brand|date=6 October 2008}}</ref>

