[[File:Benu.jpg|thumb| painting on papyrus]] [[File:A part of Giant Traditional Chinese painting 9.jpg|thumb|Rice paper is used as the substrate for this contemporary, traditionally-styled landscape painting.]] '''Watercolor paper''' is paper or substrate onto which an artists applies watercolor [[Paint|paints]], [[Pigment|pigments]] or [[Dye|dyes]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://watercolor.net/history-overview/|title=Watercolor, Watermedia, Then And Now-Early Cultures, Asian, Middle East, Early European|last=|first=|date=|website=watercolor.net|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref> There are currently many types of paper available that are manufactured for the use with watercolors. Watercolor paper can be made of wood pulp exclusively, or mixed with [[cotton]] fibers. Pure cotton watercolor paper is also used by artists though it typically costs more than paper. It is also available as an acid-free medium to help its preservation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.artistsnetwork.com/art-mediums/watercolor/understanding-the-different-grades-of-watercolor-paper/|title=Understanding the Different Grades of Watercolor Paper|date=2017-07-14|work=Artists Network|access-date=2018-10-05|language=en-US}}</ref> Watercolor paper can be described according to the manufacturing process. It can be hot pressed, cold pressed or rough. A number of companies sell watercolor papers, some of them with a long history of production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.handprint.com/HP/WCL/paper2.html|title=Handprint : light and the eye|last=MacEvoy|first=Bruce|date=August 1, 2015|website=www.handprint.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>
[[Papyrus]] was used as a 'paper' onto which the [[Egyptians]] applied their water-based paints or pigments.<ref name=":0" />
Arches, began production of watercolor paper around 1620. It provided most of the paper used in France during the 1700s. In addition to watercolor paper, Arches also produced paper that was used in documents and paper that was used as currency during the revolution in France. Arches joined other paper manufacturers in the 1950s to form Arjomari Prioux.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.handprint.com/HP/WCL/paper2a.html|title=Handprint : arches|last=|first=|date=|website=www.handprint.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>
Woven paper was used in print publication in the late 1760's because it was found to be smoother. The watercolor paper at this time was used by artists because it allowed the application of paint without the unevenness of molded paper. James Whatman created a paper specifically for use with water colors by the 1780s. He used [[gelatin]] as a sizing that created a protective coating that reduced damage to the paper by repeated wetting, drying and reworking.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/bwtr/hd_bwtr.htm|title=Watercolor Painting in Britain, 1750–1850 See works of art|last=Barker|first=Elizabeth E.|date=October 2004|website=The Metropolitian Museum of Art|series=Department of Drawings and Prints, The Metropolitan Museum of Art|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-10-04}}</ref>
